election_record.label: New Jersey 1797 U.S. House of Representatives

overview.note: The following names were listed on the original election returns, but received no votes: James Ackerman, William B. Bell, Richard Cox, William Crane, John N. Cumming, Gabriel H. Ford, James Giles, Peter Harring, James Henry, William Lin, Aaron Ogden, John Outwater, Isaac Smith, John Terrill, Abraham Westervelt, John Westervelt, M. Williamson Jr., and Anthony W. White.

Party politics were still developing in New Jersey, and the entire political arena was in a state of transition. Several of the men listed as Federalist would later become Republicans, while William Crane, a Federalist, was run on a Republican Ticket formed at Essex county in the closing week of the campaign. An excellent account of this election can be found in the book "New Jersey's Jeffersonian Republicans" (pages 18-25) by Carl E. Prince.
The New-Jersey Journal (Elizabethtown, NJ), January 18 and 25, uses the name Condict for John Condit.
The New-Jersey Journal (Elizabethtown, NJ), January 18, uses the name Conduit for Silas Condict.

sub_unit.name: Burlington
sub_unit.note: "One township is wanting in that of Burlington." Centinel of Freedom. January 18, 1797.

sub_unit.name: Fairfield
sub_unit.note: James H. Imlay received 1 vote as John Emly.

sub_unit.name: Hopewell
sub_unit.note: James H. Imlay received 5 votes as James Emly and 1 vote as John Emly.

sub_unit.name: Essex
sub_unit.note: Woods's Newark Gazette and New-Jersey Advertiser (Newark, NJ) and The Centinel of Freedom (Newark, NJ), January 18, report 860 votes for Jonathan Dayton, 456 votes for James Schureman, 474 votes for Thomas Sinnickson, 952 votes for John Condit, 75 votes for William Helmes, 92 votes for John Outwater, 462 votes for Joseph Cooper, 15 votes for Matthias Williamson, 8 votes for Silas Condict, and 39 votes for John Terrill.
The New-Jersey Journal (Elizabethtown, NJ), January 18, reports 521 votes for James Schureman in Essex County but the township totals add up 523.

sub_unit.name: Aquackanonk
sub_unit.note: The Centinel of Freedom, January 18, reports no votes for John Outwater.

sub_unit.name: Elizabethtown
sub_unit.note: The Centinel of Freedom, January 18, reports 7 votes for John Condit.

sub_unit.name: Newark
sub_unit.note: The Centinel of Freedom, January 18, reports 76 votes for Jonathan Dayton, 13 votes for James Schureman, 527 votes for John Condit, no votes for John Outwater and no votes for William Helmes.

sub_unit.name: Springfield
sub_unit.note: The Centinel of Freedom, January 18, reports 15 votes for Joseph Cooper, no votes for James Schureman, and no votes for William Helmes.

sub_unit.name: Hunterdon
sub_unit.note: The Centinel of Freedom, January 18, reports 127 votes for John Condit.

sub_unit.name: Middlesex
sub_unit.note: The Centinel of Freedom, January 18, reports 114 votes for Jonathan Dayton and 377 votes for Aaron Kitchell.

sub_unit.name: Middletown
sub_unit.note: James H. Imlay received 1 vote as James Imbly.

sub_unit.name: Sussex
sub_unit.note: On the Original Election Returns tally sheet for Sussex County, in the column for John Condit there is a numeral 6 that doesn't quite line up with any town tally, and that would make his total 13, rather than the total of 7 that is listed as the sum of the column and is written out as John Condit's official total.
